00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:24.800
connection with the Thanksgiving day
holiday. So, last day we started

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:31.000
talking about polymers,
macromolecules.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:55.420
These are chemicals that have a very
high molecular weight with a

00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:59.850
repeating chemical structure.
I've given an example here of vinyl

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:04.280
chloride as the individual molecule.
And, by addition polymerization, we

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:08.710
can break the double bond,
have it propagate, and we end up

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:13.140
with something which is the
polyvinyl chloride.

00:01:13.140 --> 00:01:17.570
N numbers can be very large,
and we can get molecular weights in

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:35.806
the vicinity of 1,000,000
grams per mole.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:26.710
We further looked at tailoring
properties by control of molecular

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:31.420
architecture. We saw that we could
look at bulk composition and form

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:36.140
such things as copolymers,
which are to polymers what alloys

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:40.850
are to metals.
Another way of tailoring properties

00:01:40.850 --> 00:01:45.570
is to vary the arrangement of the
side groups on the backbone.

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:50.280
This is the tacticity of the
polymer. And it is to a polymer

00:01:50.280 --> 00:02:08.960
what the stereoisomerism is to
individual molecules.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:58.520
And that lastly,
we looked at the shape of the

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:02.050
backbone itself,
different conformations,

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:05.580
and this is owing to the rotational
capability of the carbon-carbon bond.

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:09.110
And, at the very end of the lecture,
we looked at two forms of formation.

00:02:09.110 --> 00:02:12.640
One is addition polymerization,
which is shown here.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:16.170
We have the three stages.
We start with initiation here.

00:02:16.170 --> 00:02:19.700
You see hydrogen peroxide, which
has turned into the radical.

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:23.230
And that triggers this reaction,
which then moves the unpaired

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:26.730
electron to the end here.
And this is sticking out like a hot

00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:30.190
poker. And other gas molecules in
this case, ethylene that come in

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:33.660
contact with it will,
in turn, have their double bond

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:37.130
broken, and so on,
and so on. And finally,

00:02:37.130 --> 00:02:40.590
we get to the length that we want.
We terminate the reaction, and

00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:44.060
that's the end of the process.
The second one was condensation

00:02:44.060 --> 00:02:47.530
polymerization.
And condensation polymerization is

00:02:47.530 --> 00:03:07.260
stepwise, where you take
two different mer types.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:54.860
And here's a cartoon showing an
example of the formation of PET.

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:58.730
This is the material that's used
for soda bottles,

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:02.590
and many of the clear plastic
containers that you find in the

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:06.460
supermarket or the drugstore.
So, this one vividly indicates that

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:10.330
it, in fact, is an acid-base
reaction. I said last day,

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:14.190
you had an R1, which is a proton
donor, and an R2,

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:18.060
which is a hydroxyl donor.
Those are classical Arrhenius

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:21.870
definitions.
And so, in this case,

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:25.620
you start with terephthalic acid,
which is basically benzene, with

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:29.370
this carboxylic acid on the end.
The COOH is carboxylic acid. We'll

00:03:29.370 --> 00:03:33.120
see that repeatedly.
It's a basic group. Basic is the

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:36.870
wrong term. It's a group intrinsic
to proteins. It's an acidic group.

00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:40.620
It's not a basic group. But, basic
meaning a different way.

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:44.370
So, here's terephthalic acid.
Here's ethylene glycol. This is

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:48.120
what you put in your cooling system.
This is the same thing as Prestone

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:52.210
2 Antifreeze.
It's a double alcohol.

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:56.640
It's got hydroxyls at both ends,
it gives up one of those, combines

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:01.070
with the proton here to form water.
And then we form the amide bond,

00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:05.490
which then starts the polymer here.
And, it in fact is a polyester

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:09.920
because in the end,
you've got this COO that the O acts

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:14.350
as a bridging oxygen.
So, bridging oxygens we've seen in

00:04:14.350 --> 00:04:18.780
silicates, borates,
as critical in covalent network

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:23.070
formation.
And, they are operative here.

00:04:23.070 --> 00:04:27.210
When they are operative in polymer
systems, that type of polymer is

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:31.350
termed a polyester because the ester
linkage is this oxygen with a double

00:04:31.350 --> 00:04:35.490
bond. So, this is polyethylene
terephthalate,

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:39.640
PET as you know it.
And, the other thing that I wanted

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.780
to point out is that if you look
carefully at the structure of these,

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:47.920
last day we studied cross-linking.
And, cross-linking depended upon a

00:04:47.920 --> 00:05:07.306
covalent bridge between two chains.
And in this case,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
it's typically made with sulfur.
So, we have sulfur attacking

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
residual double bonds in the
backbone to form single bonds

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
between backbones.
So, we have two chains linking.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Well, if you look at the features
of the polymers that are made by

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
condensation polymerization,
you'll notice that in many instances,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
I think here's a good one to look at,
Kevlar. You see the carbonyl group

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
here, the C with the double
bond to the oxygen.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:24.420
And, on this side,
you have an amino group: nitrogen

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:28.850
with a hydrogen.
And, what can happen is adjacent

00:05:28.850 --> 00:05:33.280
chains can hang the aminos on one
side opposite carbonyls from the

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.710
other side. And,
look at the situation that we've set

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:42.140
up. Here's the oxygen off the
carbonyl group.

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:46.570
And, it's sitting opposite the
hydrogen off the amino group.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:06:05.673
And, you know what that can lead
to: hydrogen bonding.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:55.140
And so, in many of these
condensation polymers,

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:59.280
nylons, silicones, hydrogen bonding
acts almost as a

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:03.420
pseudo-cross-linking.
It's nowhere near as strong as a

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:07.560
true covalent cross link.
But what we do observe is that the

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:11.710
nylons, Kevlars,
things like this have much,

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:15.850
much higher strength. And, we're
going to learn a little bit later.

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:35.900
They have a higher melting point
owing to this hydrogen bonding.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:26.660
So, I think we want to just document
that: hydrogen bonding operative in

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:33.330
nylons and silicones.
And, this leads to some additional

00:06:33.330 --> 00:06:39.990
strengthening of the material.
Well, what I wanted to do today was

00:06:39.990 --> 00:06:46.660
to take up this concept that we
talked about with regard to ordering

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:52.610
versus disordering last day.
We talked about low density

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:57.840
polyethylene versus high density
polyethylene. So,

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:03.070
I want to just revisit influences on
ordering, and actually what favors

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:08.300
crystallization,
factors favoring crystallization.

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:13.530
And, remember, we are not talking
about perfect crystals here.

00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:18.760
We're talking about local ordering
over certain lengths of chain which

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:36.653
give rise to some strengthening
of the material.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:28.230
And so, I'm just going to go back
and revisit one,

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:32.460
two, and three above.
I'm going to ask, how does

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:36.700
composition, how does tacticity,
and how does conformation enhance

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:40.930
crystallization?
So, first thing: let's look at

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:45.170
composition. The way to favorite
crystallization is to make materials

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:49.410
more nearly uniform.
The higher the degree of uniformity

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:53.640
in the polymer,
the greater the chances are that it

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:57.880
can zigzag back and forth and in a
predictable manner,

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:17.560
set up these zones of crystallinity.
So, if this is a straight chain or a

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:49.000
linear chain polymer,
if it's made homogeneous of the same

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.000
composition, then the chances of its
folding back and forth on itself and

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:01.000
setting up this local sort of
semi-crystalline region are greater

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.000
than if the polymer has some random
variation in composition.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:31.830
So, the factor that favors
crystallization is having single

00:08:31.830 --> 00:08:36.660
composition. So,
homo-polymers are much more easily

00:08:36.660 --> 00:08:41.490
crystallized. So,
as an example, polyethylene oxide

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:46.330
can form crystalline polymer,
whereas if you take the polyethylene

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:51.160
oxide, block copolymer with,
say, polypropylene oxide. The

00:08:51.160 --> 00:09:09.120
second case is more likely
to be amorphous.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:09:01.550
The second factor we want to look at
is tacticity. You've got the three

00:09:01.550 --> 00:09:07.110
forms of tacticity: isotactic,
syndiotactic, and atactic. And,

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:12.660
the one that's more readily willing
to pack is going to be isotactic.

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:18.220
So, isotactic version will be
favored from the standpoint

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:24.100
of crystallization.
And, we have evidence that isotactic

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:30.300
polystyrene is highly crystalline.
So, when you see some of these hard

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:47.833
polystyrene containers,
they are predominately isotactic,

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:22.700
whereas atactic polystyrene is
dominantly amorphous.

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:28.900
So, there's the influence of
tacticity. And the third

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:54.330
one is conformation.
How does conformation act?

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:58.990
Well, we've got the linear chains.
We've got branched chains, and

00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:03.660
we've got cross-linked chains.
And clearly, following this

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:08.330
paradigm, the linear chains are
favored when it comes to the

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:12.990
formation of ordered structures.
So, if you look at something like

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:17.660
high density polyethylene,
that's shown here, this is the

00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:22.230
opaque milk jug.
This has a high degree of linearity

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:26.690
in the chains,
whereas branching or cross-linking

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:31.150
are going to make things very
difficult from the perspective of

00:10:31.150 --> 00:10:35.610
forming crystalline structures.
And, in fact, here's something

00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:40.070
that's volume versus temperature.
It should remind you of the unit

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:44.530
that we have just covered in
silicate glasses.

00:10:44.530 --> 00:11:03.593
We see the cooling curves here at
two different rates.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:53.710
And, fast cooling as a knee in the
curve at a higher glass transition

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:58.420
temperature than slow cooling.
And, similarly, with fast cooling,

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:03.140
there is a higher degree of quenched
in free volume.

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:07.850
So, all those ideas apply.
The other thing I want to look at

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:12.570
now is on the basis of what we've
seen so far, what are the properties

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:17.280
of polymers? We can tailor things
to a great extent.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:36.026
But there are certain properties
that they all share.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:28.180
So, let's document those.
First one: electrical insulators.

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:34.360
Why? Whenever I ask why, we have
to look at electronic structure.

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:40.540
Here, we have strong covalent bonds
up and down the backbone.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:46.720
And, we have relatively weak van
der Waals bonds with some hydrogen

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:52.900
bonding in between.
In no case are we looking at free

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:59.710
electrons.
So: strong covalent bonds internally.

00:11:59.710 --> 00:12:07.140
These are intramolecular bonds,
no free electrons. With covalent

00:12:07.140 --> 00:12:14.570
bonds, we have electron sharing and
we have octet stability and the

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:30.006
electrical insularity that
accompanies that.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Second, optically,
optical behavior, while they're

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:18.000
transparent to visible light,
again, the high-strength covalent

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:26.000
bonds transparent to visible light,
and in the case of amorphous, when

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:52.350
amorphous, they are clear.
When amorphous,

00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:57.050
they are clear. And,
when we have the semicrystalline

00:12:57.050 --> 00:13:01.760
setup, regions of higher atom
density, which translate into

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:06.460
regions of higher refractive index.
And since the refractive indices

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:11.170
are not matched between the
amorphous and the semicrystalline

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:15.880
regime, this acts effectively as an
interface that can scatter light.

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:20.580
So, the semi-crystalline, although
they are formally transparent to

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:25.290
visible light,
these in fact prove to be opaque as

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:43.780
you can see from the appearance
of that milk jug.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:34.360
Now, the question you've got to ask
is, could you generate

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:38.720
semicrystalline zones that were
either index matched or on a length

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:43.090
scale shorter than that of visible
light? We saw that in the inorganic

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:47.450
case with the difference between
Pyroceram glass and visions.

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:51.810
The only difference was that the
crystallites in visions were

00:13:51.810 --> 00:14:08.953
much, much smaller.
And as a result,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:43.000
we were able to get the
strengthening effect without

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:49.000
incurring the penalty of opacity.
The third one is chemically inert.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Polymers are chemically inert.
Again, the strong covalent bonds,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
octet stability, same reasons. And
this leads to their extensive use in

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:07.000
packaging, packaging especially of
foods and beverages.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:32.070
Foods and beverages exploit this
property. And,

00:14:32.070 --> 00:14:37.150
lastly, they are solid at room
temperature. The long molecules,

00:14:37.150 --> 00:14:42.220
even though they're only weak van
der Waals bonds operative between

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:47.300
molecules, remember,
the strong covalent bonds are within

00:14:47.300 --> 00:14:52.380
the molecule. If you want to ask
the question, is something solid,

00:14:52.380 --> 00:14:57.460
liquid, or gas, you have to ask, how
does one molecule bond to another

00:14:57.460 --> 00:15:15.920
one of identical composition?
And for that, we got not strong

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:49.000
covalent bonds,
but we've got weak van der Waals

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:55.000
bonds. But, they are operating over
such large contact areas.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:01.000
These molecules are very,
very long.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So, the long molecule presents a
high surface to volume ratio,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:21.000
very high surface to volume ratio.
And, that leads to strong bonding.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:31.000
And ultimately, it leads to
entanglement.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:57.590
So, we have entanglement.
We have weak van der Waals bonds

00:15:57.590 --> 00:16:04.190
over high surface to volume ratio.
And, that leads to solidity at room

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:10.790
temperature. And,
we recognized last day that absent

00:16:10.790 --> 00:16:17.390
cross-linking can reprocess these by
reheating. This gives us

00:16:17.390 --> 00:16:33.313
thermoplastics that
can be reprocessed.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:28.330
And even in the case of hydrogen
bonding, although the nylons have to

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:32.660
go slightly higher temperatures.
We are able to reprocess the nylons.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:36.990
In the case of cross-linking,
of course, we have to go to other

00:16:36.990 --> 00:16:41.330
measures because heating to very,
very high temperatures capable of

00:16:41.330 --> 00:16:45.660
breaking the cross links would also
break the backbone.

00:16:45.660 --> 00:17:04.653
So, these things become not very
easily recyclable.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:54.610
And, in fact, what I've got here is
the recycle codes which you see on

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:59.220
